# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: anja-karliczek
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] A federal election was held on 22 September to elect the members of the 18th Bundestag of Germany.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] At stake were all 598 seats to the Bundestag, plus 33 overhang seats determined thereafter.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] The Christian Democratic Union of Germany/Christian Social Union of Bavaria (CDU/CSU) of incumbent chancellor Angela Merkel won their best result since 1990 with nearly 42% of the vote and nearly 50% of the seats, just five short for an overall majority.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] The co-governing Free Democratic Party (FDP) failed to meet the 5% vote electoral threshold in what was their worst showing ever in a federal election at the time, the electoral wipeout denying them seats in the Bundestag for the first time in their history.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] As the CDU/CSU's narrowly missed a majority, and the FDP failed to get any seats, any prospective government was required to be a new coalition.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] The only possible coalition government excluding the CDU/CSU would have been an all-left-wing red–red–green coalition, since a red–green alliance, similar to the German government between 1998 and 2005, would not have enough seats for a majority.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] Both the Social Democratic Party of Germany (SPD) and Alliance 90/The Greens ruled out governing with The Left that had ruled former East Germany.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] Ultimately, Merkel's party reached a coalition agreement with the then-main opposition party, the SPD, to form another grand coalition, the third in the country's history since World War II.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] The SPD leadership conducted a ratification vote by their broader membership before the agreement was made final.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] This grand coalition was renewed after the 2017 German federal election due to failure during the negotiations of a Jamaica coalition.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] The date of the federal election is governed by the Basic Law for the Federal Republic of Germany (Germany's constitution) and the Federal Election Law (*Bundeswahlgesetz*).
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] Article 39 of the Basic Law states that the Bundestag shall be elected between 46 and 48 months after the beginning of the legislative period.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] As the 17th Bundestag convened on 27 October 2009, the election was scheduled between 27 August and 27 October 2013.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] To avoid school holidays, a date in late September is usually chosen; this made 15 or 22 September 2013 the most likely dates.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] The President of Germany ordered 22 September 2013 to be the election day upon the recommendation of the federal government.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] Polling stations were open from 8:00 to 18:00.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] According to Article 38 of the Basic Law for the Federal Republic of Germany, members of the Bundestag shall be elected in general, direct, free, equal, and secret elections; everyone over the age of eighteen is entitled to vote.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] In 2008, some modifications to the electoral system were required under an order of the Federal Constitutional Court of Germany.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] The court had found a provision in the Federal Election Law by which it was possible for a party to experience a negative vote weight, namely losing seats due to more votes, violated the constitutional guarantee of the electoral system being equal and direct.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] The court allowed three years for these changes, so the 2009 German federal election was not affected.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] The changes were due by 30 June 2011 but appropriate legislation was not completed by that deadline.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] A new electoral law was enacted in late 2011 but was declared unconstitutional once again by the Federal Constitutional Court upon lawsuits from the opposition parties and a group of some 4,000 private citizens.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] The Bundestag approved and enacted the new electoral reform in February 2013.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] The Bundestag is elected using mixed-member proportional representation, meaning that each voter has two votes, a first vote for the election of a constituency candidate by first-past-the-post and a second vote for the election of a state list.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] The Sainte-Laguë/Schepers method is used to convert the votes into seats, in a two-stage process with each stage involving two calculations.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] First, the number of seats to be allocated to each state is calculated, based on the proportion of the German population living there.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] Then the seats in each state are allocated to the party lists in that state, based on the proportion of second votes each party received.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] In the distribution of seats among state lists, only parties that have obtained at least five percent of the valid second votes cast in the electoral area or have won a seat in at least three constituencies are taken into consideration.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] The minimum number of seats for each party at federal level is then determined.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] This is done by calculating, for each party state list, the number of constituency seats it won on the basis of the first votes, as well as the number of seats to which it is entitled on the basis of the second votes.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] The higher of these two figures is the party's minimum number of seats in that state.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] Adding together the minimum number of seats to which the party is entitled in all of the states produces a total representing its guaranteed minimum number of seats in the country as a whole.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] In order to ensure that each party receives its guaranteed minimum number of seats when the seats are allocated using the Sainte-Laguë/Schepers method, it may become necessary to increase the number of seats in the Bundestag.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] Then it must be ensured that the seats are distributed to the parties in line with their national share of the second votes.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] Additional overhang seats, or balance seats, are created to ensure that the distribution of the seats reflects the parties' share of the second votes and that no party receives fewer than its guaranteed minimum number of seats.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] Balance seats are also necessary to ensure that each party requires roughly the same number of second votes per seat.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] Once the number of seats which each party is entitled to receive across the country has been determined, the seats are allocated to the parties' individual state lists.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] Each state list must receive at least as many seats as the number of constituencies which the party won in the state in question.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] Although the chancellor-candidates (*Kanzlerkandidaten*) play a very important role in election campaigns, their office is not regulated in any law, and it is up to each party to determine how, and if at all, to name a chancellor-candidate.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] The SPD names a chancellor-candidate, while the CDU and the CSU name a common one.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] The smaller Bundestag parties (the FDP, the Left, and the Greens) usually do not name a chancellor-candidate as it is very improbable for such a candidate to actually be elected chancellor.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] They instead name one or two persons (*Spitzenkandidaten*) who are to become the faces of that party's campaign.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] While a sitting chancellor is usually named chancellor-candidate for his or her own party, the main opposition party's process to determine their chancellor-candidate differs.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] Most times, such a person is determined in an inner party circle and then anointed in a party convention.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] As the CDU/CSU is the main government party, CDU chairwoman and incumbent chancellor Angela Merkel was not challenged as chancellor-candidate.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] In the SPD, the situation was a bit less clear, as there were four candidates in the discussion.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] Gabriel, Steinmeier, and Steinbrück all had a bad electoral record, as they all had led their party into painful defeats in state or general elections.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] Gabriel and Steinbrück lost their inherited minister-president offices in 2003 and 2005, and Steinmeier failed as a chancellor-candidate in 2009.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] On 28 September 2012, the party announced that Steinbrück would be the SPD's chancellor-candidate.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] After taking heat domestically for bailing out other European countries, Finance-Minister Wolfgang Schäuble took the step of mentioning that Greece would need a third bailout.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] This was in stark contrast to his colleagues who had refrained from making such measures in light of the election, in particularly following Merkel's dismissal of a potential future bailout.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] In reaction to the statement and the dithering, Peer Steinbrueck of the SPD said that it was "time that Mrs.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] Merkel tells people the truth", while Jürgen Trittin of the Greens also criticized Merkel.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] Her visit was welcomed by residents of the town due to its historic nature but was also suggested as a vote ploy ahead of the election.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] She also campaigned on Germany's unemployment record that fell to a two-decade low during her premiership, progress towards a balanced budget, and the Eurozone's advantages for Germany's exports.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] There were questions asked about her legacy and a potential heir to the party leadership.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] Campaigning in the "hot phase" ended on 21 September, as Merkel appealed to voters to support her against Eurosceptics.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] A 90-minute televised debate between the lead candidates of the CDU/CSU and the SPD, the two leading contenders, was held on 1 September.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] The smaller-party top-ranking candidates Rainer Brüderle (FDP), Jürgen Trittin (Alliance 90/The Greens), and Gregor Gysi (The Left) held a separate debate on 2 September.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] In Germany, there are regular opinion polls during the whole of the legislative period.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] Germany's major polling agencies are Allensbach, Emnid, Forsa, Forschungsgruppe Wahlen, GMS, Infratest dimap, and INSA/YouGov.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] August 2013 opinion polls suggested that the CDU/CSU and the FDP (black–yellow coalition) would be just short of or just above an absolute majority, rather than the SPD and Greens (red–green coalition), partners in Gerhard Schröder-led government (1998–2005).
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] Only four parties were present in the Bundestag for the first time since the 1987 West German federal election, as the CDU/CSU operates as one Bundestag group.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] The Christian Democratic Union of Germany (CDU) and the Christian Social Union of Bavaria (CSU) scored 42 percent of the vote, their best result since tallying 44% in 1990.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] Since 15.7 percent of the vote went to parties that fell short of the 5% electoral threshold, the CDU/CSU came up just five seats short of a majority.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] The Free Democratic Party (FDP), junior partner in the outgoing coalition government, failed to pass the 5% threshold.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] It also failed to win any directly elected seats, as it has not won any directly elected seats since 1990, shutting it out of the Bundestag altogether for the first time in the party's history.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] A new Eurosceptic party, Alternative for Germany, nearly won seats but was shut out by narrowly missing the 5% electoral threshold.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] Below are second votes (*Zweitstimme*, or votes for party list), by state.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] Incumbent chancellor Angela Merkel said: "It was a strong vote to take responsibility in Germany, but also in Europe and the world." Peer Steinbrück announced his withdrawal from top politics and his intention to focus on his ordinary tasks as a member of parliament.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] As in the red-baiting and Red Scare campaign ("red socks") during the 1994 German federal election, Merkel scared off that the alternative was a left-wing red–red–green coalition government, since the FDP lost all its seats.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] Many SPD insiders did not want to work with The Left.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] One day after the election, Merkel announced that she had already spoken with the SPD but would not rule out other possibilities.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] The Greens were open to coalition talks with the CDU/CSU, but CSU leaders said they opposed a coalition with the Greens.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] The Greens announced they would not consider going into coalition with the Left.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] Formal talks began in the first week of October when Merkel met SPD leaders on 4 October.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] She said: "Europe is watching us, the world is watching us.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] We have the common responsibility to build a stable government." She also planned to hold talks with the Greens the following week.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] After five weeks of negotiations that culminated in an all-night session 27–28 November, the CDU/CSU reached agreement with the SPD to form a new coalition government.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] Issues resolved in the talks included the planned introduction of a minimum hourly wage of €8.50 in 2015 and no new taxes.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] The deal depended on approval by the SPD rank and file, with a poll set for 6 December.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] On 14 December, 76% of the SPD's members voted for the coalition to go ahead.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] The Third Merkel cabinet was sworn in on 17 December.
[src:anja-karliczek/2013-german-federal-election] This grand coalition continued after the 2017 German federal election.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] A federal election was held in Germany on 26 September 2021 to elect the members of the 20th Bundestag.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] State elections in Berlin and Mecklenburg-Vorpommern were also held.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Incumbent chancellor Angela Merkel, first elected in 2005, chose not to run again, marking the first time that an incumbent Chancellor of the Federal Republic of Germany did not seek re-election.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] With 25.7% of total votes, the Social Democratic Party of Germany (SPD) recorded their best result since 2005, and emerged as the largest party for the first time since 2002.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The ruling CDU/CSU, which had led a grand coalition with the SPD since 2013, recorded their worst ever result with 24.1%, a significant decline from 32.9% in 2017.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Alliance 90/The Greens achieved their best result in history at 14.7%, while the Free Democratic Party (FDP) made small gains and finished on 11.4%.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The Alternative for Germany (AfD) fell from third to fifth place with 10.4%, a decline of 2.3 percentage points.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The Left suffered their worst showing since their official formation in 2007, failing to cross the 5% electoral threshold by just over one-tenth of a percentage point.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The party was nonetheless entitled to full proportional representation, as it won three direct mandates.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The South Schleswig Voters' Association (SSW) was exempt from the 5% threshold and won 1 seat, the first time it held national representation since 1949.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] With a fifth grand coalition being dismissed by both the CDU/CSU and the SPD, the FDP and the Greens were considered kingmakers.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] On 23 November, following complex coalition talks, the SPD, FDP and Greens formalized an agreement to form a traffic light coalition, which was approved by all three parties.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Olaf Scholz and his cabinet were elected by the Bundestag on 8 December.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Irregularities in Berlin led to repeat elections in February 2023 (state) and February 2024 (federal).
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The result of the federal repeat election meant that the FDP lost a seat in the Bundestag, while 3 other seats were moved from Berlin to different states.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The 2017 federal election was held after a four-year grand coalition between the CDU/CSU and the SPD.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Though the CDU/CSU remained the biggest parliamentary group, both it and the SPD suffered significant losses.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The SPD leadership, recognising the party's unsatisfactory performance after four years in government, announced that it would go into opposition.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] With the CDU/CSU having pledged not to work with either the AfD or The Left before the federal election, the only remaining option for a majority government was a Jamaica coalition consisting of the CDU/CSU, FDP, and the Greens.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Exploratory talks between the parties were held over the next six weeks, though the FDP withdrew from the negotiations on 20 November, citing irreconcilable differences between the parties on migration and energy policies.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Chancellor Angela Merkel consulted with President Frank-Walter Steinmeier, who implored all parties to reconsider in order to avoid fresh elections.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The SPD and their leader Martin Schulz indicated their willingness to enter into discussions for another coalition government with the CDU/CSU.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The SPD leadership voted to enter into exploratory discussion on 15 December 2017 and at a party congress in January 2018 a majority of the party's delegates voted to support the coalition talks.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The text of the final agreement was agreed to by the CDU/CSU and the SPD on 7 February, though was conditioned on the approval of a majority of the SPD's party membership.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The 463,723 members of the SPD voted to approve or reject the deal from 20 February to 2 March, with the result announced on 4 March.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] A total of 78.39% of members cast valid votes, of which 66.02% voted in favor of another grand coalition.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Merkel was voted in by the Bundestag for a fourth term as chancellor on 14 March, with 364 votes for, 315 against, 9 abstentions, and 4 invalid votes, just 9 more votes than the 355 needed for a majority.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The new government was officially referred to as the Fourth Merkel cabinet.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Merkel's final government was subject to intense instability.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The 2018 German government crisis saw the longstanding alliance between the CDU and CSU threaten to split over asylum seeker policy.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Interior Minister and CSU leader Horst Seehofer threatened to undercut Merkel's authority by closing German borders for asylum seekers registered in another European Union (EU) country.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The split, eventually repaired following a summit with EU countries, threatened to bring down the government.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Following his party's historically low result in the 2018 Bavarian state election, Seehofer was replaced as CSU leader by new Bavarian Minister-President Markus Söder at a party conference in January 2019, while he retained his position as Interior Minister in the Fourth Merkel cabinet.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] In October 2018, Merkel announced that she would resign as leader of the CDU at the party's conference in December 2018 and step down as Chancellor of Germany at the forthcoming election, following poor results at state elections for the CSU in Bavaria and for the CDU in Hesse.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Merkel's allegedly preferred candidate for the party leadership, Annegret Kramp-Karrenbauer, narrowly defeated Friedrich Merz, who had been a rival of Merkel around 2002 and had left politics in 2009 criticising her decisions and leadership.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] A party convention to elect a new leader was scheduled for April but was repeatedly delayed due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The election was held in January 2021, with Armin Laschet, incumbent Minister-President of North Rhine-Westphalia, winning with 52.8% of delegate votes.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The other party in the coalition government, the SPD, also had leadership instability.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Following their worst general election result since 1945, at the beginning of the new government the party elected Andrea Nahles as their leader in April 2018.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Nahles had already been elected leader of the SPD parliamentary group after the federal election in September when the party still planned to go into opposition.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] She was unsuccessful in improving the party's stock with the electorate as it continued to slide in opinion polls and was for the first time in history well beaten by the centre-left party Alliance 90/The Greens at the 2019 European Parliament election.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] She resigned on 2 June 2019, precipitating a leadership election for the SPD.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Progressive candidates Norbert Walter-Borjans and Saskia Esken defeated the more moderate candidates Olaf Scholz and Klara Geywitz, and were elected co-leaders by the party's membership.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Their election raised prospects of the coalition government collapsing and early elections being called, although Reuters reported that the duo would seek to achieve agreement from the CDU/CSU on increasing public spending rather than allow the government to collapse.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] In August 2020, the party appointed Merkel's deputy Vice-Chancellor Scholz as its candidate for chancellor at the election, despite him having lost to Walter-Borjans and Esken in the party leadership election.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Cem Özdemir and Simone Peter stood down as co-leaders of the Greens after the failed Jamaica negotiations, and Annalena Baerbock and Robert Habeck were elected as their successors in January 2018.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Dissatisfaction with the SPD and the federal government saw a rise in Greens' polling numbers throughout 2018.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] They scored record results in the Bavarian and Hessian state elections in October and subsequently surpassed the SPD in public opinion, settling in second behind the CDU/CSU for the next three years.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The party had its best ever showings at the 2019 European Parliament election, 2020 Hamburg state election, and 2021 Baden-Württemberg state election.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] They briefly polled in first place during two brief periods, first after the 2019 European Parliament election and again after the nomination of chancellor candidates in April 2021.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The Left also underwent a change in leadership, with Katja Kipping and Bernd Riexinger stepping down after nine years as party co-leaders.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] They were succeeded by Janine Wissler and Susanne Hennig-Wellsow at a party conference held digitally on 27 February 2021.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Wissler is considered a member of the party's left wing, formerly aligned with the Socialist Left faction, while Hennig-Wellsow is considered a moderate and part of the party's pragmatic wing.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Both support their party's participation in federal government, particularly Hennig-Wellsow, who played a major role in the red–red–green coalition government of The Left, the SPD, and the Greens in the state of Thuringia.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Germany uses the mixed-member proportional representation system, a system of proportional representation combined with elements of first-past-the-post voting.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The Bundestag has 598 nominal members, elected for a four-year term; these seats are distributed between the sixteen German states in proportion to the states' number of eligible voters.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Each voter can cast two votes: a constituency vote (first vote) and a state party list vote (second vote).
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Based solely on the first votes, 299 members are elected in single-member constituencies by first-past-the-post voting.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The second votes are used to produce a proportional number of seats for parties, first in the states, and then in the Bundestag.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Seats are allocated using the Sainte-Laguë method.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] If a party wins fewer constituency seats in a state than its second votes would entitle it to, it receives additional seats from the relevant state list.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Parties can file lists in every single state under certain conditions, such as a fixed number of supporting signatures.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Parties can receive second votes only in those states in which they have filed a state list.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] To qualify for proportional seat distribution, a party must receive more second votes nationwide than the electoral threshold of 5%.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] This requirement is waived for parties winning at least three single-member constituencies.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] As result of this waiver, parties have benefited on three occasions, such as the DP in the 1957 West German federal election and the PDS in the 1994 German federal election.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Parties representing recognized national minorities are exempt from the electoral threshold.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] As of 2021, these minorities are the Danish, Frisians, Sorbs, and Romani people.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Under this rule, the 2021 federal election had to take place on a Sunday between 29 August and 24 October (inclusive), as the previous 19th Bundestag had held its first sitting on 24 October 2017.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The President of Germany sets the exact date for the election.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] On 9 December 2020, President Frank-Walter Steinmeier ordered the election to be held on 26 September 2021.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] For the fourth time since 2009, the 2021 federal election was observed by OSCE, providing four experts from three OSCE states.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The Center for Monitoring, Analysis and Strategy (CeMAS) found that false claims of voter fraud had become commonplace on Telegram in Germany, with accusations against Dominion Voting Systems being common despite the company's technology not being used in German elections.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] CeMAS researcher Miro Dittrich said, "We have seen far-right actors try to claim election fraud since at least 2016, but it didn't take off.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The table below lists the parliamentary groups of the 19th Bundestag.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] After the election of Minister-President of North Rhine-Westphalia, Armin Laschet as federal CDU chairman in January 2021, he became the presumptive CDU nominee for the Union's joint chancellor candidacy.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Laschet was challenged by Minister-President of Bavaria Markus Söder of the CSU, who consistently polled well among voters and had been discussed as a potential candidate since mid-2020.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] As the contest intensified in March/April 2021, Söder was backed by the CSU as well as some state and local CDU associations, while Laschet received the support of most of the CDU.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The two men failed to come to an agreement by the given deadline of 19 April, leading the federal CDU board to hold an impromptu meeting to break the deadlock.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The board voted 31 to 9 in favour of Laschet.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] After the vote, Söder announced his support for Laschet as chancellor candidate.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] On 10 August 2020, the SPD nominated incumbent Vice Chancellor and Finance Minister Olaf Scholz as their lead candidate for the election.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Scholz, who served as Mayor of Hamburg from 2011 to 2018, unsuccessfully sought the SPD leadership in the 2019 leadership election.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Scholz was formally elected at a party conference on 8–9 May 2021, supported by 96% of delegates.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The AfD's lead candidates were chosen via a membership vote held from 17 to 24 May 2021.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The ticket of party co-chairman Tino Chrupalla and Bundestag co-leader Alice Weidel were elected with 71% of votes; they were opposed by the ticket of former German Air Force lieutenant-general Joachim Wundrak and MdB Joana Cotar, who won 24%.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] 14,815 votes were cast, corresponding to a turnout of 48%.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] On 21 March 2021, the FDP association in North Rhine-Westphalia elected federal chairman Christian Lindner as top candidate for the party list in that state.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] He was re-elected as chairman on 14 May, winning 93% of votes with no opponent.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The vote also served to confirm him as lead candidate for the federal election.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The Left announced Janine Wissler and Dietmar Bartsch as their co-lead candidates on 2 May 2021.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Wissler was elected federal party co-leader earlier in the year alongside Susanne Hennig-Wellsow, who chose not to seek the co-lead candidacy.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Bartsch had co-chaired The Left's Bundestag group since 2015, and was previously co-lead candidate in the 2017 federal election.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Wissler and Bartsch were formally selected by the party executive on 8–9 May, receiving 87% of the votes.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Due to their rise in national opinion polling since 2018, the Greens were expected to forgo the traditional dual lead-candidacy in favour of selecting a single chancellor candidate.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Party co-leaders Annalena Baerbock and Robert Habeck were considered the only plausible candidates.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Baerbock was announced as chancellor candidate on 19 April.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Both Baerbock and Habeck were co-lead candidates for the party's election campaign.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] A total of 47 parties and lists were approved to run in the 2021 federal election, including the seven which won seats in the 19th Bundestag.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Of these, 40 ran party lists in at least one state, while 7 ran only direct candidates.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] In addition, 196 independent candidates ran in the various direct constituencies.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] In the table below, green shading indicates that the party ran a list in the indicated state.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The number in each box indicates how many direct candidates the party ran in the indicated state.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] In July 2021, the respective state electoral committees rejected the lists of the AfD in Bremen and the Greens in Saarland.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The AfD list was rejected for formal reasons, while the Green list in Saarland was declared invalid due to a controversial nomination process, in which one third of the state delegates were excluded from the nomination convention.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Both state parties filed motions against the rulings.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The federal electoral committee dismissed the motion of the Saarland Greens, while the AfD list in Bremen was permitted to run in the elections.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The Green Party will thus not be eligible for the proportional vote in Saarland for the first time in the party's history.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The federal election was impacted by incumbent chancellor Angela Merkel's decision not to run again, and candidates to present themselves as the natural successor to Merkel.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The 2021 European floods, with at least 184 deaths in western parts of Germany, put the climate issue back on the agenda in July.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The SPD called for "everything to be done to stop global warming," while the CDU/CSU wanted to "speed up climate protection measures".
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] By the end of July, 56 per cent of Germans believed that the floods made it "even more important than before" to combat climate change, and 73 per cent believed the government was not doing enough in this area; only the AfD's supporters were overwhelmingly of the opposite opinion.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Following those events, six people under the age of 30 began a hunger strike in front of the Reichstag building at the end of August.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] They demanded a sincere dialogue with the leaders of the main political parties before the elections and the establishment of a citizens' convention to decide on ambitious measures for the climate.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] During the deadly 2021 floods, while visiting Erftstadt on 18 July, the CDU/CSU lead candidate Armin Laschet was caught laughing on camera and making jokes while President Frank-Walter Steinmeier was speaking.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Laschet was heavily criticized, despite his apology saying: "It was stupid and shouldn't have happened and I regret it." Both the CDU/CSU and Laschet's ratings suffered heavily in opinion polls and the SPD took the lead.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] During the campaign, Scholz rejected tax cuts for the rich as immoral, pledged to "increase taxes on the wealthy, spend on cleaner technology and expand social programs", and a minimum wage increase to 12 euros.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] One SPD delegate was quoted as saying: "To prepare the ground for a robust and functioning coalition, you need to make sure that no one walks out of talks looking like a loser.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] In its election manifesto, The Left called for abolishing NATO in favour of a "collective security system with Russia's involvement", to which Scholz said that this is an example of minimum criteria to govern which is not negotiable.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The Left's lead candidates stated that those demands are a tribute to the party's historic anti-imperialist roots rather than reflecting ambitions to govern at the federal level and a discussion on the future of NATO is also being led by centrists such as France's Emmanuel Macron.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The party struck the anti-NATO demand from its immediate policy measures and Janine Wissler responded that foreign policy was more than NATO.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Gregor Gysi, a member of the left wing of the party, stated that such demands are more of a vision, are not to be implemented as soon as possible, and should not be seen as inflexible preconditions for a left-wing coalition.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The Greens see foreign policy differences with The Left as big as financial and debt disagreements with the FDP.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The Left joining the federal government would have broken a taboo due to being a democratic successor of East Germany's ruling party, and for its pacifist and anti-militarist stance, and could be seen as following examples in Spain and Sweden.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] A traffic light coalition (SPD–FDP–Greens) was seen as the more likely scenario but a R2G coalition, which would be favoured by the left-wing leadership and rank-and-file party members, was not excluded if coalition talks with FDP fail due minimum wage increase or the wealth tax.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] For the first time since 2002, the four major television broadcasters (public services ZDF and ARD with its regional networks, and commercial networks RTL and ProSieben/Sat.1) did not hold a joint television debate of only the major candidates from CDU/CSU and SPD.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Separate debates were previously prevented by incumbent chancellor Merkel, but she did not run for a fifth term in 2021, and Armin Laschet represented CDU/CSU.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The Greens had only finished 6th in the 2017 election, but from mid-2018 to mid-2021 were ranked as 2nd in polls, even first in spring of 2021.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Thus, with the traditional Two-party system of Union and SPD getting broken up and expanded to three on the federal level.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] For the first time, the traditional two-way duel debates became a three-way truel, dubbed "Triell".
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Additional four-way debates, in 2025 called *Quadrell*(quadrel), were held with leaders of the smaller parties that were part of the parliament.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Although the vote share of the South Schleswig Voters' Association (0.12%) was well below the 5% electoral threshold, due to its status of being representative of a recognised minority group (Danes and Frisians), an exception in federal law allowed the party to win one party-list seat.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Incumbents are denoted in bold and followed by *(I)*.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] In Berlin, vote casting and counting was not simple as the federal election was on the same day as the Berlin Marathon, the 2021 Berlin state election and a local referendum.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The Federal Returning Officer felt compelled to request a report from the State Returning Officer Petra Michaelis.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] In some polling stations ballot papers were missing or ran out and could not be delivered on the same day due to the Berlin marathon.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Ballot papers (of which there were 115 different variants in Berlin) and postal voting documents were also swapped.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Many votes were cast long after the official end of voting at 6 p.m, the last after 8 p.m. when the outcome was already being forecast.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] At least one polling station was closed due to missing documents.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] In at least 16 Berlin polling stations, basic election data did not match (including impossible voter turnouts of over 100%).
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] On 29 September 2021, Michaelis announced her resignation and that of her deputy.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] In 2022, the 2021 Berlin state election was declared invalid, to be replaced by the February 2023 Berlin repeat state election.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Decision making on the federal level took even longer.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] In late 2023, a repeat of the federal election was ordered in 455 of 2,256 Berlin precincts.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The result of the repeat election on 11 February 2024 replaced the original result in those precincts, resulting in the overall result of the election being recalculated.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] As a result of the repeat election, the FDP lost a seat in Berlin, resulting in the size of the Bundestag being reduced from 736 to 735 members.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The SPD, Greens, and The Left each lost a seat in Berlin, while gaining one in Lower Saxony, North Rhine-Westphalia, and Hesse respectively, thus keeping the total number of seats won by those parties unchanged.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] For the first time since 2002, the SPD emerged as the largest party in the Bundestag.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Also for the first time since 2002, the SPD swept all single-member constituency seats in the states of Brandenburg and Saarland, where they defeated cabinet ministers Peter Altmaier and Annegret Kramp-Karrenbauer.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] They also won all constituencies in Mecklenburg-Vorpommern for the first time, including Vorpommern-Rügen – Vorpommern-Greifswald I, the seat of outgoing chancellor Angela Merkel.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] It was also the first time they won any single-member constituency seats in Saxony-Anhalt and Thuringia since 2005.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The SPD had been written off by many political observers due to longtime internal quarrels and poor performances in prior elections, even those in early 2021.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] In the 2019 European Parliament election, they dropped to a historic low 15.8%, accelerating the decline of already deeply embattled and unpopular leader Andrea Nahles.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] When the unpopular and little-known SPD leaders Norbert Walter-Borjans and Saskia Esken nominated moderate Olaf Scholz, whom they had unexpectedly defeated in the 2019 leadership election, as Chancellor candidate in August 2020, they were widely mocked.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The SPD sat at a distant third place in the polls and stayed there until their sudden surge late in the campaign.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] However, even at their historic poll lows around 14%, Olaf Scholz had a significantly higher personal approval rating than both his party and the other Chancellor candidates Laschet and Baerbock.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] After the extreme personal unpopularity, resulting from gaffes and scandal, meant that first Baerbock and then Laschet floundered, the SPD took the lead, for the first time since early 2017, in the final stretches of the election campaign.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] This surge also meant that some "paper candidates", a lot of them young, were unexpectedly elected to the Bundestag, for example Jan Plobner, Jakob Blankenburg or Fabian Funke.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] That being said, the surge and eventual outcome of the election was mainly decided by older voters, who switched from the CDU/CSU to the SPD, which some attributed to Scholz being very similar in his calm and moderate leadership style to incumbent Angela Merkel.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The CDU/CSU had their worst result ever by far, eclipsing the previous worst of 31% in 1949.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] There was speculation that chancellor candidate Armin Laschet would lose election to the Bundestag; he was placed first on the North Rhine-Westphalia party list, and if the CDU gained overhang seats, that list would not be used.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Due to the CDU's bad performance in terms of single-member constituency seats, Laschet was elected to the Bundestag.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The first time since 2005 that they did not win all single-member constituency seats in Bavaria, the CSU also had their worst result in history.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Reasons given for the catastrophic defeat were corruption scandals of several CDU/CSU politicians in spring 2021, some minor allegations even being brought against Laschet himself.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] In addition, Laschet was suffering from extreme personal unpopularity, even in his own state.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Laschet did not have the incumbency advantage that helped moderately popular Merkel to win re-election three times, but still had to run on Merkel's legacy in voters minds.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] This meant that the otherwise popular CDU/CSU platform of increasing digitization, reducing bureaucracy and moderate climate action were not taken seriously as his party had not addressed them in sixteen years of government in the minds of many voters.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] In one infamous campaign moment, Laschet spoke of a "Wind of Change" in his closing statement in the first three way debate, which was widely ridiculed.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The contentious decision by the CDU establishment to have him run as CDU/CSU candidate instead of the much more popular CSU leader Markus Söder also played into this.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] During the belligerent internal selection process in spring, polls showed Söder faring a lot better than Laschet in the election, often higher than the 2017 result, and Söder was the preferred candidate of the base and the public at large.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Even fairly late into the election campaign, 70% of CDU/CSU supporters wanted to replace Laschet with Söder.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Söder publicly supported and defended Laschet, even on election night, but was accused of backstabbing Laschet's candidacy in order to become chancellor candidate in 2025.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Laschet took responsibility for the result, but initially refused to resign in hopes of becoming Chancellor through a Jamaica coalition.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The ensuing talks were plagued by leaks damaging Laschet and after Söder prematurely declared the talks to be over, both Greens and FDP decided to enter coalition talks with the SPD instead.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] After intense pressure from his party and the public, Laschet announced on 8 October 2021 that he would step down but would moderate the next CDU leadership election.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] That leadership contest was the first to be decided by party members, who overwhelmingly chose conservative outsider Friedrich Merz in December 2021, after he failed in the previous two leadership elections, to Annegret Kramp-Karrenbauer in 2018 and Laschet in January 2021.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] This was seen as a rebuff to the party establishment, who had backed Kramp-Karrenbauer and Laschet, both seen as being more moderate, aligned in both policy positions and leadership style to Angela Merkel.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The Greens got their best result in history, nearly doubling from 2017.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Their slump in the polls was largely attributed to a number of gaffes from and the personal unpopularity of Annalena Baerbock, though polls show that a lot of Green voters migrated to the SPD in the final weeks of the campaign to ensure the CDU would not form government.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Though she won in the party-list, Baerbock lost in Potsdam – Potsdam-Mittelmark II – Teltow-Fläming II to SPD's Olaf Scholz by a large margin.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] In addition, though the Greens won 16 single-member constituency seats, all of them except Flensburg – Schleswig, the constituency of future Vice Chancellor Robert Habeck, were entirely urban constituencies.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The Greens were also disqualified from running on the Saarland state list due to irregularities in the selection of list candidates.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The Greens had, however, won only one seat in the Saarland in the previous two federal elections.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The FDP had their second best showing since German reunification, gaining a few seats to maintain its fourth-place position.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] This was enough to make it a kingmaker alongside the Greens in coalition talks.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Like the Greens, they did well with young voters; among first-time voters, they received the highest vote share of 23%.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] In addition, while they only marginally improved their result in the West German states, their more significant increase in support in former East Germany amounted to their best performance there in the party's history.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The AfD lost seats and went from the third largest party and Leader of the Opposition to the fifth largest party in the Bundestag; however, they performed strongly in former East Germany, where they won 16 single-member constituency seats in Saxony, Saxony-Anhalt, and Thuringia.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] While the AfD lost vote share in Saxony, the stronger losses of the CDU still allowed them to place ahead of the CDU, becoming the most voted party in Saxony.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] They also won the most party list votes in Thuringia, though only by 0.6%.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Reasons given for their drop in support include far less media attention, largely due to the open Chancellor's race, and large swaths of anti-lockdown and anti-vaccination voters, which the AfD campaigned hard on, voting for new parties like dieBasis and Free Voters.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Leader of the AfD faction in the Bundestag Dr.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Alice Weidel was widely ridiculed for claiming on election night that they surpassed their 2017 result if one added the results for dieBasis and Free Voters.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The Left had their worst showing since 2002, when it was the Party of Democratic Socialism, slumping from 69 seats in 2017 to just 39, or 4.9%.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Under a longstanding electoral law intended to benefit parties with regional appeal (as is the case with the Left in the old East Germany), any party that wins at least three constituency seats is entitled to its share of proportionally-elected seats, regardless of vote share.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Apart from this symbolic defeat, their preferred government, a left-wing red–red–green coalition, did not have a majority in the new Bundestag, and the German financial market rallied as a result.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Vice President of the Bundestag Petra Pau lost her single-member constituency of Berlin-Marzahn-Hellersdorf by a large margin.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The seat had been held by The Left and its predecessor parties since the 1990 federal election.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Reasons given for the massive slump were public quarrels in the party.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] These public feuds intensified after the election, for example, the convicted former head of government of East Germany Hans Modrow, who chairs The Left's "council of elders", denounced the party.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] From February 2022 onwards, the Russian invasion of Ukraine put a strain on The Left.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Also, due to the irregularities during the 2021 elections in Berlin, affecting state level and federal level results, both elections were under ongoing scrutiny.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] According to court decision in 2022, the state election was repeated as a whole by the February 2023 Berlin state election, with losses for The Left.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] A possible upcoming 2024 repeat of the federal election in parts of Berlin was a threat to the faction status of The Left in the Bundestag, and to 38 of 39 members, with only the direct seat gained in Saxony being not affected.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] With the Bündnis Sahra Wagenknecht establishing itself in October 2023 with 10 parliament members, the faction of The Left was dissolved in late 2023, losing funding and privileges by getting demoted to a group, or two in that case.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The 2021 election was a watershed moment for candidates with a migration background.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] In terms of representation of ethnic minorities, one source suggested that the Bundestag would have 24 new MPs with "Balkan" ancestry.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Its list included, however, largely people of Turkish ancestry who mostly have roots in Anatolia.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The South Schleswig Voters' Association (SSW), a regionalist party only contesting Schleswig-Holstein representing the Danish and Frisian minorities in Southern Schleswig, won their first seat, becoming the first regionalist party to win seats since 1953.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Recognized minority parties are exempt from the threshold of 5%, which is how the SSW won a seat with 0.1% of the vote nationwide.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The SSW last contested in 1961 and last won a seat in 1949.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] They named a felt discrimination of Northern Germany as reason for them contesting the election.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Stefan Seidler was seated as their Member of the German Bundestag.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Seidler was offered to sit in the SPD parliamentary group as a guest by their leader Rolf Mützenich, but declined.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Minor parties did exceptionally well in the 2021 election.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The left-wing satire party Die PARTEI had their best result ever, as did the Animal Protection Party and the regionalist Free Voters, which doubled their result and received 7.5% in Bavaria, where they take part in the state government.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] A few new minor parties emerged in the 2021 election, the most notable being the Anti-lockdown and Anti-vaccination dieBasis party, which received between 1 and 1.9%.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Team Todenhöfer, founded in 2020 by notorious former CDU Member of the German Bundestag Jürgen Todenhöfer, also first contested the 2021 election, running on anti-militarism and receiving support from pro-Palestinian groups, but only garnered 0.5% of the vote.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The 2021 election also accelerated the decline of the far-right National Democratic Party, which only got 0.1% of the vote.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The NPD was at a time the most successful minor/fringe party, getting 1.6% in 2005 and entering various state parliaments in former East Germany.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] A three-party governing coalition, with the FDP and the Greens joining either the SPD or CDU/CSU, was discussed as a likely outcome.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] While the grand coalition of the CDU/CSU and SPD could have been renewed, numerous representatives of both the CDU/CSU and the SPD ruled out this option before the federal election, during the campaign, and after.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] On election night, SPD leader Scholz reiterated his goal to form a government, citing the fact that his party emerged as the largest in parliament.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] He expressed his intention to become chancellor and his preference for a traffic light coalition with the FDP and the Greens.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Leading figures in the CDU/CSU such as Michael Kretschmer stated that since the CDU/CSU was knocked down to second place, it should not form the government.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The FDP and the Greens, having won 210 seats between them, announced that they would talk separately before deciding on whom to support as a senior coalition partner.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The Greens and the FDP held discussions for two days after the election.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] On 7 October, the two parties met with the SPD for the first round of exploratory talks, with a second round on 11 October.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] On 15 October, the SPD agreed to more ambitious climate targets, as pledged by the Greens.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] On 17 October, the Greens voted to enter formal coalition talks with the SPD and FDP.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The next day, the FDP voted to do the same.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The 20th Bundestag was officially sworn in on 26 October.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] On 16 November, the general secretaries of the three traffic light coalition parties (SPD, FDP, Greens) announced that an agreement document was almost complete, with Scholz to become Chancellor, and that the details would be issued some time in the next week.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] On 23 November, an agreement for a traffic light coalition was finalised.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The three parties announced a number of policies, including plans to phase out coal energy by 2030, eight years ahead of the previous target, as well as lower the federal voting age to 16 years, raise the minimum wage to €12 per hour, and lower barriers to acquiring German citizenship.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Annalena Baerbock will become foreign minister, while Robert Habeck will head a new "super ministry" with responsibility for climate, energy, and economy.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Christian Lindner will become finance minister.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The SPD convention voted 98.8% in favour of approving the agreement on 4 December, followed by the FDP with 92.4% on 5 December.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The results of the Greens membership ballot were announced on 6 December, with 86% voting to approve the coalition.
[src:anja-karliczek/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Scholz was elected as Chancellor by the Bundestag on 8 December, with 395 votes of 707 cast, with 303 votes against.
[src:anja-karliczek/2022-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The **2022 North Rhine-Westphalia state election** was held on 15 May 2022 to elect the 18th Landtag of North Rhine-Westphalia.
[src:anja-karliczek/2022-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The outgoing government (First Wüst cabinet) was a coalition of the Christian Democratic Union (CDU) and Free Democratic Party (FDP) led by Minister-President Hendrik Wüst.
[src:anja-karliczek/2022-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The CDU remained the largest party with 36% of votes, a small increase from 2017, while the opposition Social Democratic Party (SPD) declined to 27%.
[src:anja-karliczek/2022-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The Greens almost tripled their vote share to 18%.
[src:anja-karliczek/2022-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The FDP fell sharply to 6%, and the Alternative for Germany (AfD) slipped to 5%.
[src:anja-karliczek/2022-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] Overall, the incumbent coalition lost its majority, though the opposition SPD and Greens also fell short of victory.
[src:anja-karliczek/2022-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] After the election, CDU formed a coalition with the Greens.
[src:anja-karliczek/2022-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] This was the first time the two parties had worked together on the state level in North Rhine-Westphalia.
[src:anja-karliczek/2022-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] Hendrik Wüst was re-elected as Minister-President on 28 June, and his cabinet was sworn in the next day.
[src:anja-karliczek/2022-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The Landtag is elected for five years, with its term commencing when the new Landtag first meets.
[src:anja-karliczek/2022-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] Elections must take place in the last three months of the legislative period.
[src:anja-karliczek/2022-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The Landtag is elected via mixed-member proportional representation.
[src:anja-karliczek/2022-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] 128 members are elected in single-member constituencies via first-past-the-post voting.
[src:anja-karliczek/2022-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] 53 members are then allocated using compensatory proportional representation.
[src:anja-karliczek/2022-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] Voters have two votes: the "first vote" for candidates in single-member constituencies, and the "second vote" for party lists, which are used to fill the remaining seats in a way that achieves proportionality overall.
[src:anja-karliczek/2022-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The minimum size of the Landtag is 181 members, but if overhang seats are present, proportional leveling seats will be added to ensure proportionality.
[src:anja-karliczek/2022-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] An electoral threshold of 5% of valid votes is applied to the Landtag; parties that fall below this threshold are ineligible to receive seats.
[src:anja-karliczek/2022-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] In the previous election held on 14 May 2017, the CDU became the largest party with 33.0% of votes cast, an increase of seven percentage points.
[src:anja-karliczek/2022-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The SPD lost eight points and placed second with 31.2% of votes.
[src:anja-karliczek/2022-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The AfD contested its first election in North Rhine-Westphalia, winning 7.4%.
[src:anja-karliczek/2022-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] Other parties were not able to enter parliament, The Left only closely missing the electoral threshold of 5% winning 4.9% (+2.4 pp).
[src:anja-karliczek/2022-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The SPD had led a coalition with the Greens since 2010 (→ cabinets Kraft I und Kraft II), but this government lost its majority in the election.
[src:anja-karliczek/2022-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The CDU subsequently formed a coalition with the FDP, and Armin Laschet became Minister-President (→ Cabinet Laschet).
[src:anja-karliczek/2022-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] After unsuccessfully leading the CDU/CSU in the 2021 German federal election, Laschet resigned as Minister-President.
[src:anja-karliczek/2022-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] Hendrik Wüst was elected by the Landtag as his successor on 27 October 2021.
[src:anja-karliczek/2022-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The table below lists parties represented in the 17th Landtag of North Rhine-Westphalia.
[src:anja-karliczek/2022-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The results of the election were widely interpreted in the German press as a rebuke of German chancellor Olaf Scholz's and the SPD's response to the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine.
[src:anja-karliczek/2022-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] In the initial days after the Russian invasion, Scholz promised greater military spending and aid to Ukraine but in the following months was seen as indecisive about exporting heavy weapons to Ukraine.
[src:anja-karliczek/2022-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] Germany has also been less willing than other European nations to boycott Russian energy imports.
[src:anja-karliczek/2022-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] North Rhine-Westphalia is located in the industrial heartland of Germany and has traditionally been the base of support for the SPD.
[src:anja-karliczek/2022-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The Greens largely benefited from the collapse in support for the SPD, as many of their policies on Ukraine are more popular with the German public.
[src:anja-karliczek/2022-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The FDP's result was interpreted as coming from their federal ministers enjoying far less popularity than those of the Greens, popular Christian Lindner not running again, and many 2017 FDP voters migrating to the CDU to prevent Kutschaty from becoming Minister-President.
[src:anja-karliczek/2022-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] Since the incumbent coalition of the CDU and FDP lost its majority in the election, the formation of a new government was necessary.
[src:anja-karliczek/2022-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The Greens were considered to hold the balance of power, able to enter into coalition either with the CDU or with the SPD and FDP.
[src:anja-karliczek/2022-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] They held separate talks with the CDU and SPD.
[src:anja-karliczek/2022-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The FDP declined to participate, believing a CDU–Green government was inevitable.
[src:anja-karliczek/2022-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The Greens continued exploratory talks with the CDU and began formal coalition negotiations on 31 May.
[src:anja-karliczek/2022-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] In a draft agreement, the two sides proposed transitioning North Rhine-Westphalia to climate neutrality, phasing out coal by 2030, and building 1,000 additional wind turbines over five years.
[src:anja-karliczek/2022-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] They also agreed to hire 10,000 additional teachers and ensure equal pay for teachers regardless of the type of school they are employed in.
[src:anja-karliczek/2022-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] On 10 June, the two parties announced plans to finalise and approve a coalition agreement by 25 June, with Wüst to be re-elected as Minister-President on 28 June.
[src:anja-karliczek/2022-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] They also agreed to phase out regulations banning wind turbines from being built within 1,000 metres of residences.
[src:anja-karliczek/2022-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The cabinet would comprise the Minister-President, seven CDU ministers, and four Greens.
[src:anja-karliczek/2022-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The coalition agreement was approved near-unanimously by a CDU conference on 25 June.
[src:anja-karliczek/2022-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The same day, it passed the Greens congress with 85%.
[src:anja-karliczek/2022-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] There were objections from members who criticised the proposed separation of the agriculture portfolio from the environment ministry.
[src:anja-karliczek/2022-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] The state Green Youth rejected the prospect of coalition with the CDU outright, stating they could not sufficiently address pressing issues such as climate change, affordability, and rent and housing.
[src:anja-karliczek/2022-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] Wüst was re-elected as Minister-President by the Landtag on 28 June, winning 106 votes out of 180 cast, plus one abstention.
[src:anja-karliczek/2022-north-rhine-westphalia-state-election] Fourteen deputies were absent, including four from the CDU and one from the Greens.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Like earlier cellular systems, 5G networks divide service areas into smaller zones called cells, which are served by fixed cell sites.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Compatible devices connect by radio to local base stations, which are linked to an operator's core network and to external networks such as the Internet through backhaul connections.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] 5G can be deployed using low-band, mid-band, and high-band radio spectrum, with coverage and performance depending heavily on the frequencies used, network design, congestion, and device capabilities.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Compared with 4G, 5G is designed to provide higher data rates, greater network capacity, lower latency, improved support for dense device deployments, and more flexible network management.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Actual user speeds are typically much lower than peak values and vary by operator, location, spectrum band, signal quality, and network load.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] 5G is used for mobile broadband, fixed wireless access, private and industrial networks, and machine-type communications.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Its standards support features such as network slicing, edge computing, non-public networks, and ultra-reliable low-latency services, although these capabilities are not present in every deployment.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] The rollout of 5G has required new spectrum allocations and upgrades to radio access, transport, and core-network infrastructure.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] It has also raised issues involving deployment cost, energy use, vendor security, and public claims about radio-frequency health effects.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] 5G is being deployed alongside 4G networks and is expected to coexist with them for many years.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] In 2008, NASA and the Machine-to-Machine Intelligence Corporation (M2Mi) conducted nanosatellite communication studies that influenced early next-generation network concepts.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] In 2012, New York University established NYU Wireless, a research center focused on millimeter-wave communication.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] The same year, the University of Surrey founded the 5G Innovation Centre, funded by £35 million from public and industry partners including Huawei and Samsung.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Also in 2012, the European Union launched the *Mobile and Wireless Communications Enablers for the Twenty-Twenty Information Society (METIS)* project to align emerging network research with international standardization.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] In 2013, the ITU-R Working Party 5D began studies on *IMT-2020*, later formalized as the 5G standard.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] During the same period, major firms such as Samsung Electronics, NTT Docomo, and Huawei conducted early trials.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Samsung tested a prototype achieving more than 1 Gbit/s across 2 km using 8 × 8 MIMO antennas.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] NTT Docomo received a government award at CEATEC for high-speed network development, while Huawei announced a US$600 million program to advance mobile network technology.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] On April 3, 2019, South Korea launched its national network, the first full commercial deployment.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Hours later, Verizon began limited service in select U.S. cities.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] In June 2019, Globe Telecom introduced the Philippines' first next-generation network, and in December 2019, AT&T launched a consumer service in the United States that expanded nationwide during 2020.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Commercial 5G deployment expanded rapidly through 2020.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Beyond public mobile networks, it was also adopted in private industrial and enterprise systems, including operation in unlicensed spectrum (NR-U) and licensed non-public networks (NPNs).
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Private 5G networks became important for Industry 4.0 automation and smart manufacturing.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Early rollouts used non-standalone (NSA) mode—with 4G cores—before networks transitioned to standalone (SA) mode with dedicated 5G cores.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] South Korea’s 2019 rollout used equipment from Samsung, Ericsson, and Nokia; LG U Plus also deployed Huawei hardware.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Samsung supplied most of the roughly 86,000 sites, while SK Telecom, KT Corporation, and LG U Plus concentrated coverage in major cities using the 3.5 GHz band under NSA operation.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Reported download speeds averaged 200–400 Mbit/s, and subscriptions grew from about 260,000 to 4.7 million during 2019.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Following these early deployments, T-Mobile US launched the first nationwide standalone network in 2020.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Ericsson projected that by the mid-2020s, 5G networks would reach about 65 percent of the global population.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Major suppliers of 5G radio and core systems included Altiostar, Cisco Systems, Datang Telecom/Fiberhome, Ericsson, Huawei, Nokia, Qualcomm, Samsung, and ZTE.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Huawei was estimated to hold about 70 percent of global 5G base stations by 2023.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] By 2022, network speeds in many regions had stabilized, and operators began testing 5.5G upgrades to improve capacity and latency.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] By the early 2020s, large-scale commercial 5G networks were active across most developed markets, and rollout in developing regions was still accelerating.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Small cells are low-power radio nodes that extend network capacity in dense or indoor areas.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] They operate over short distances, typically a few dozen to a few hundred metres, and are used to maintain coverage for mmWave signals.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Massive multiple-input multiple-output (MIMO) systems use large antenna arrays to increase capacity and spectral efficiency.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] They extend conventional MIMO by serving multiple users simultaneously and steering signals toward them to reduce interference.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Beamforming directs radio energy toward specific users.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] In analogue beamforming, antenna outputs are combined to focus signal power in one direction.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Digital beamforming transmits data streams across multiple layers to improve signal strength and reliability.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Non-orthogonal multiple access assigns different power levels to users sharing the same frequency resources to improve spectral efficiency.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] 5G NR uses polar codes for control channels and low-density parity-check codes (LDPC) for data channels, replacing the turbo codes used in 4G.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Research has explored the use of 5G mmWave networks for wireless power transfer.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Studies using wavelengths between 1 mm and 10 mm remain experimental.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] The 5G core (5GC) is a service-oriented, software-defined system that separates control and user planes and supports flexible deployment.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] It replaces the 4G Evolved Packet Core with modular, software-based network functions.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Software-defined networking (SDN) and network function virtualization (NFV) enable software-based configuration, scaling, and management of networks.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Together with network slicing, these technologies support applications such as the Internet of things, connected vehicles, and industrial automation.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Service-based architecture (SBA) integrates SDN and NFV principles and replaces the 4G EPC framework with modular network functions that communicate through RESTful APIs.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Each function registers with a network repository function (NRF), which enables independent scaling and interoperability.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Each network function performs a defined role within the 5G core, replacing or extending elements from the 4G EPC.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] 5G networks use multiple parts of the radio spectrum.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] They operate across three main frequency ranges—low, mid, and high bands—which balance speed, coverage, and signal quality differently.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Between 2016 and 2019, regulators in many regions, including the United States and the European Union, reallocated large sections of spectrum for 5G through auctions and new licensing rules.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] By 2019, more than 50 countries had assigned or planned to assign 5G frequencies.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] In 3GPP Release 16, the standard added 5G NR-U, allowing operation in both unlicensed and licensed spectrum.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Low- and mid-band 5G provide broad coverage and reliable indoor reception.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] High-band signals weaken rapidly and may lose over 100 dB when passing through common building materials.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Operators use beamforming antennas, small cells, and signal repeaters to extend range and improve indoor coverage.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Technologies such as License Assisted Access (LAA) and LTE-WLAN Aggregation (LWA) let mobile networks share unlicensed spectrum with Wi-Fi.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Cloud-based RAN systems and dense small-cell layouts help narrow the performance gap between cellular and Wi-Fi links.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] The ITU-R defines three main application areas for 5G: enhanced mobile broadband (eMBB), ultra-reliable low-latency communications (URLLC), and massive machine-type communications (mMTC).
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] These categories describe the main uses of 5G: faster mobile connections (eMBB), highly reliable and responsive communication (URLLC), and large-scale links between machines (mMTC).
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] By 2020, eMBB was widely deployed, while URLLC and mMTC were still in development.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Enhanced mobile broadband (eMBB) provides much faster internet and higher capacity than 4G.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] It supports intensive data use in busy areas such as city centres, stadiums, and transport hubs.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Ultra-reliable low-latency communications (URLLC) are designed for time-critical applications such as factory automation, remote medical procedures, and traffic systems.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Shorter transmission delays improve precision and reliability.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Massive machine-type communications (mMTC) connect large numbers of low-power devices such as sensors and meters.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] These networks underpin the Internet of things (IoT) by allowing machines to exchange data autonomously in industry, transport, and urban systems.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] 5G is used in transport, manufacturing, and energy systems that require constant, low-latency communication.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] The 5G Automotive Association develops vehicle-to-everything (C-V2X) standards that allow cars to exchange safety information with nearby vehicles and infrastructure.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Drones and autonomous vehicles use 5G for navigation, remote control, and real-time data transmission.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Low-latency connections also enable digital twin models—virtual copies of machines or buildings that show real-time performance data used for monitoring and maintenance.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] 5G extends to public safety, broadband access, and media delivery.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Emergency services use it for live video, data, and reliable push-to-talk communication.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Fixed wireless access (FWA) provides home and business broadband using 5G radio links instead of wired connections, especially in rural areas where laying cables is costly.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] 5G Broadcast trials in Europe show that local 5G networks can deliver live television and radio to many devices simultaneously without using mobile data plans.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Voice over NR (VoNR) allows phone calls to be made over 5G's internet-based network, similar to Voice over LTE (VoLTE) on 4G.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] 5G can deliver much higher data rates than 4G, up to ten times faster.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Theoretical peak download speeds reach up to 20 Gbit/s.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] In practice, average 5G download speeds in the United States have been measured at about 186 Mbit/s by T-Mobile, while South Korea in 2022 led globally with averages near 430 Mbit/s.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] 5G networks are also designed to provide much greater total capacity and efficiency than 4G, with up to a hundredfold projected increase.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] The most widely deployed version, sub-6 GHz (mid-band) 5G, provides speeds of roughly 10–1000 Mbit/s with wider reach than mmWave bands.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] C-Band (n77/n78) was introduced in the U.S. in 2022, though activation by Verizon and AT&T was briefly delayed due to FAA safety concerns.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] The highest 5G speed measured in a deployed network is 5.9 Gbit/s (2023).
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Low-band frequencies such as n5 cover larger areas per cell but deliver lower data rates of around 5–250 Mbit/s.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Typical *air latency* for 5G is around 8–12 ms, excluding retransmissions and handovers.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Verizon reported about 30 ms latency in early deployments.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Edge servers located near base stations can reduce round-trip time to roughly 14 ms and minimize jitter to about 1.8 ms.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Latency increases substantially during handovers, ranging from 50 to 150 ms depending on network conditions.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Ongoing research focuses on reducing these interruptions by adjusting handover margins and time-to-trigger parameters.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] 5G uses adaptive modulation and coding schemes (MCS) to maintain a low block error rate (BLER).
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] When the error rate exceeds a threshold, the system automatically switches to a lower MCS to prioritize reliability over speed.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] The range of 5G varies with transmit power, frequency, and interference.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] High-frequency mmWave bands (e.g., n258) have a shorter range than mid-band (n78), which in turn has a shorter range than low-band (n5).
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Operators use network simulation and drive testing to measure the actual range and coverage of these bands, as real-world performance can differ from marketing claims.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] The term 5G was first associated with the International Telecommunication Union's IMT-2020 standard.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] It defines peak download and upload rates of 20 and 10 Gbit/s.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] The 3rd Generation Partnership Project (3GPP) later proposed its 5G New Radio (NR) technology for IMT-2020.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Early FR1 deployments reusing 4G infrastructure (non-standalone mode) have been reported to provide 15–50 percent higher throughput than advanced 4G networks under favorable conditions.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] 5G networks can operate in Non-Standalone (NSA) mode using existing LTE infrastructure or Standalone (SA) mode using a dedicated 5G Core (5GC) network.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Other organizations also contribute to 5G standards.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] The DECT-2020 specification defines DECT NR+, a non-cellular, mesh-based radio system recognized by ITU as part of 5G.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] The IEEE defines standards for wired links between the remote radio unit (RRU) and the baseband unit (BBU).
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] 5Gi was developed in India by IIT Madras, IIT Hyderabad, the Telecommunications Standards Development Society India (TSDSI) and the Centre of Excellence in Wireless Technology (CEWiT).
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] It extends 5G coverage in rural and remote areas through low-mobility large-cell (LMLC) configurations.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] 5Gi was merged in April 2022 into the global 5G NR standard in 3GPP Release 17.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] In the Internet of things (IoT), 3GPP defines the evolution of NB-IoT and eMTC to support low-power wide-area applications such as connected sensors and meters.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] 3GPP standards also define advanced communication services for voice and connected devices.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] 3GPP defines Voice over NR as a technology that enables native, high-quality voice over a 5G Standalone network through the 5G System Architecture.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Unlike early 5G Non-Standalone deployments that relied on Evolved Packet System Fallback, VoNR integrates directly with the IP Multimedia Subsystem (IMS) used in VoLTE.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] It uses NAS protocols to establish high-priority QoS flows that support URLLC requirements for voice traffic.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Support for 5G Standalone is a prerequisite for VoNR.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] VoNR benefits from the enhanced security architecture of the 5G Core network, including improved subscriber identity protection.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] VoNR delivers superior audio quality through the Enhanced Voice Services (EVS) codec, which must adhere to rigorous terminal acoustic requirements and standardized testing procedures.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Most phones released since 2023 (such as the iPhone 15 series and newer flagship devices) support VoNR, but availability depends on carrier enablement in specific areas.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] 3GPP also defines non-terrestrial networks (NTN) that use satellites and airborne platforms to provide coverage where ground networks are impractical.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] 5G-Advanced, also known as 5.5G or 5G-A, is defined in 3GPP Release 18 as a transition between 5G and 6G.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] It adds features for more efficient spectrum use, lower energy demand, and higher reliability.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] The release introduces AI- and ML-based network management, extended-reality services, and communication support for autonomous systems.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Release 18 specifies improved time-synchronization methods independent of the GNSS and built-in geolocation functions.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] It extends non-terrestrial support to satellite and airborne communication.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] 5G Reduced Capability (RedCap) in 3GPP Release 17 is designed to bridge the gap between high-performance 5G devices and low-power IoT technologies such as LTE-M and NB-IoT.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] It was created to address use cases between Enhanced Mobile Broadband (eMBB), Ultra-Reliable Low-Latency Communications (URLLC), and Massive Machine-Type Communication (mMTC) technologies.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] The Global Mobile Suppliers Association (GSA) compiled the first database of 5G-compatible products, listing 23 manufacturers and 33 models across categories such as smartphones, hotspots, and customer-premises equipment.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Later surveys recorded more than one hundred announced products from over fifty vendors.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Early 5G modem chipsets were released by Intel, MediaTek, Qualcomm, and Samsung, followed by additional platforms in subsequent product generations.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] The Samsung Galaxy S10 5G was among the first smartphones to support 5G networks.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Other early 5G models included the Nokia 8.3 5G, designed for operation across low- to mid-band frequencies; the Google Pixel 5 and Pixel 4a (5G); and Apple's iPhone 12 series, the company's first generation with 5G capability.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] By the early 2020s, most high-end smartphones featured 5G capability, while some consumer devices still lack full support.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] As a result, the practical benefits for mid range phone users have been modest, and 5G adoption has lagged behind expectations.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] In 2019, the European Commission and the European Union Agency for Cybersecurity (ENISA) warned that 5G networks could expand potential attack surfaces for state actors, recommending diversification of suppliers.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Nokia and Ericsson are the only European manufacturers.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Researchers from ETH Zurich and partner universities found weaknesses in the 5G authentication process that could expose users to new security risks.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] They concluded that the system was still immature and that its higher data capacity could increase exposure to attacks.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] A 2022 study identified a design flaw in the Evolved Packet System (EPS) that could affect device behavior during network switching.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Growth of the Internet of things increases the number of devices connected through 5G.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] IoT Analytics estimated growth from about 7 billion devices in 2018 to over 21 billion by 2025, raising exposure to DDoS attacks, cryptojacking, and other cyberattacks.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Concerns about espionage and data access have influenced national policies.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] The United States, Australia, and the United Kingdom have restricted or banned Chinese-made equipment.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] A 2012 report by the United States House Permanent Select Committee on Intelligence concluded that equipment from Huawei and ZTE could pose national-security risks.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Later assessments by U.S. intelligence agencies warned that Huawei products could allow covert data access.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] In 2022, the FBI reported that Huawei equipment near U.S. military bases could interfere with nuclear communications.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Huawei and the Chinese government deny the allegations.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Analysts note that China's National Security Law could require companies to provide data to authorities if requested.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] In 2020, the United States Department of State launched The Clean Network initiative to promote data privacy and security among allied nations.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] By year-end, more than 60 countries and 200 telecommunications companies had joined, including most NATO, EU, and OECD members.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Some 5G bands, such as n258 at 26 GHz, are close to frequencies used for passive remote sensing by weather and Earth observation satellites, including water vapor measurements at 23.8 GHz.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Interference with satellite observations could reduce the accuracy of numerical weather prediction models and affect sectors such as commercial aviation.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Navy warned that out-of-band emissions from 5G transmissions near 24 GHz could degrade forecasts by up to 30 %.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] The 2019 World Radiocommunication Conference set an interim limit of −33 dBW until 2027, followed by −39 dBW.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] The World Meteorological Organization (WMO) and European Centre for Medium-Range Weather Forecasts (ECMWF) warned that these limits could reduce forecast reliability.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] In 2021–2022, the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) warned that some 5G signals could interfere with aircraft radar altimeters, which operate at 4.2–4.4 GHz, while new 5G services use 3.7–4.0 GHz.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Europe uses lower frequencies (3.4–3.8 GHz), reducing the risk.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Some 5G allocations overlap with frequencies used by C band satellite communication systems.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Interference can occur when networks operate in 3.3–3.6 GHz, near satellite reception at 3.4–4.2 GHz Mitigation uses low-noise block downconverters and waveguide filters.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] 5G and Wi-Fi 6E share the 6 GHz band, which enables efficient spectrum use but requires coordination to prevent interference.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Both operate under unlicensed conditions in the US and EU, supporting NR-U and Wi-Fi 6E technologies.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Analysts note that marketing of 5G has often overstated its capabilities.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Common concerns include limited user benefits, short range of mmWave signals, and rebranding of non-5G improvements as 5G.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] A 2020 survey by McKinsey & Company found that operators identified few immediately profitable use cases.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Consumer surveys show mixed attitudes, with skepticism about marketing claims and uneven coverage in early deployments.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Industry groups and network operators state that 5G enables faster speeds and lower latency, though results depend on infrastructure rollout and available spectrum.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] In contrast to the initial excitement about the prospects, many firms striving for deployment have encountered reality, users are not eager to upgrade the technology.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Five years after its launch, a majority of users have yet to transition to the new standard.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Public concern about the effects of wireless signals predates 5G technology.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Similar concerns were raised about earlier mobile standards in the 1990s and 2000s.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] According to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC), "exposure to intense, direct amounts of non-ionizing radiation may result in tissue damage due to heat.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Some critics argue that existing exposure limits are too lenient or influenced by industry lobbying.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Claims that the use of 5G mobile networks can cause cancer are unsupported by scientific evidence.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Several books making unverified claims about wireless health effects have been published.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] One, by Joseph Mercola, alleged links to ADHD, heart disease, and brain cancer.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Mercola was criticized for promoting misinformation during the COVID-19 pandemic and warned by the Food and Drug Administration (FDA) for selling unapproved COVID-19 cures.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] According to *The New York Times*, controversy regarding 5G health effects partly originated from an unpublished 2000 report by physicist Bill P.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Curry for the Broward County School Board, which incorrectly concluded that higher-frequency microwaves are absorbed more deeply by the brain.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Later analyses showed that this was a misunderstanding of *in vitro* research results.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Experts noted that millimeter-wave frequencies used by 5G cannot penetrate the skin or reach internal organs.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] In a 2019 article, the same newspaper reported that RT America promoted claims linking 5G to diseases such as brain cancer, infertility, and Alzheimer's disease.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] The network aired several such programs in 2019, later cited by numerous blogs and websites.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] In 2019, cities such as Brussels and Geneva temporarily halted 5G rollouts pending radiation assessments.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] The Swiss Telecommunications Association stated that studies had not demonstrated adverse health effects from 5G exposure.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Similar debates occurred in the Netherlands, the United States, and the United Kingdom, where some municipalities briefly delayed deployments or issued precautionary statements.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] The Food and Drug Administration maintains that existing exposure limits for cellphone radiofrequency energy are sufficient to protect public health.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Low-level electromagnetic fields (EMF) can have measurable biological effects in plants and animals, but research remains inconclusive about health risks to humans.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] A 2019 meta-analysis found that while many *in vitro* and *in vivo* studies detected biological responses to radiofrequency exposure, the evidence did not establish health risks.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] The rollout of 5G technology began during the COVID-19 pandemic, prompting conspiracy theories that linked 5G to the pandemic.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] These claims led to arson attacks on telecom masts in parts of Europe, including the Netherlands, the United Kingdom, and Italy.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] In the United Kingdom, at least 61 mobile masts were reportedly set on fire.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] During the early months of the pandemic, Australian anti-lockdown protesters carried anti-5G signs, later connected to broader conspiracy groups.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] The second claims that 5G causes COVID-19.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Some versions claim the pandemic hid illnesses blamed on 5G, while others suggest COVID-19 began in Wuhan, one of the first cities with early 5G rollout.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] The marketing of pre-5G technologies refers to the promotion of enhanced 4G networks as precursors or alternatives to 5G.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] Before and during early 5G deployment, some mobile network operators used terms such as "pre-5G", "5G-ready", "4.5G", and "5G Evolution" for upgraded LTE Advanced or LTE Advanced Pro networks.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] These networks could use features such as carrier aggregation, 256-QAM, and 4×4 MIMO to increase data rates, but they did not use 5G NR, the radio access technology standardized for 5G networks.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] A notable example was 5G Evolution, introduced by AT&T in 2017 to market higher-speed LTE service.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] AT&T described the service as "a foundation for our evolution to 5G while the 5G standards are being finalized", but technology publications criticized the branding as misleading because the underlying network remained based on LTE technologies rather than 5G.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] In 2019, Sprint sued AT&T, alleging that the 5G Evolution and "5GE" branding misled consumers into believing that they were receiving 5G service.
[src:anja-karliczek/5g] In 2020, the National Advertising Review Board recommended that AT&T stop using "5G Evolution" and related claims in advertising, finding that the terms were misleading; AT&T said it disagreed with the decision but would comply with the self-regulatory process.
[src:anja-karliczek/aaron-valent] In 2023, Aaron Valent ran for the district council election in Lower Franconia and studied in the meantime at the Julius Maximilian University of Würzburg.
[src:anja-karliczek/aaron-valent] At the time of his election to the Bundestag, Valent was training as a legal assistant.
[src:anja-karliczek/aaron-valent] He is a member of the Bavarian state executive committee of the Left Party.
[src:anja-karliczek/achim-post] Post became a member of the Bundestag in the 2013 German federal election.
[src:anja-karliczek/achim-post] In parliament, he was a member of the Joint Committee.
[src:anja-karliczek/achim-post] From 2015 to 2023, Post led the Bundestag group of SPD parliamentarians from North Rhine-Westphalia, the largest delegation within the party's parliamentary group.
[src:anja-karliczek/achim-post] From 2017, he served as one his parliamentary group's chairpersons, under the leadership of successive chairs Andrea Nahles (2017–2018) and Rolf Mützenich (2018–2025).
[src:anja-karliczek/achim-post] In addition to his committee assignments, Post was part of the German-Egyptian Parliamentary Friendship Group.
[src:anja-karliczek/achim-post] In September 2024, Post announced that he would not stand in the 2025 federal elections but instead resign from active politics by the end of the parliamentary term.
[src:anja-karliczek/adam-balten] Balten moved from Poland to Germany with his parents at the age of five.
[src:anja-karliczek/adam-balten] He speak Polish language fluently and his ties to his birth country are still close.
[src:anja-karliczek/adam-balten] He often visited his grandparents and family in Poland.
[src:anja-karliczek/anja-karliczek] Karliczek was born in Ibbenbüren and grew up in Tecklenburg.
[src:anja-karliczek/anja-karliczek] After an apprenticeship at Deutsche Bank in Osnabrück, she moved to work in her family's hotel in 1993.
[src:anja-karliczek/anja-karliczek] While raising a family and working full-time, Karliczek studied business administration at University of Hagen from 2003 until 2008, with a diploma thesis analysing the fiscal advantages of transferring pension obligations from the employer’s point of view.
[src:anja-karliczek/anja-karliczek] Karliczek joined the CDU in 1998 and became the party's local chair in Tecklenburg in 2011.
[src:anja-karliczek/anja-karliczek] Karliczek has been a member of the Bundestag since the 2013 elections, representing Steinfurt III.
[src:anja-karliczek/anja-karliczek] Between 2013 and 2018, she was a member of the Finance Committee, where she served as the CDU/CSU parliamentary group’s rapporteur on occupational and fully funded pension schemes and employee shareholding.
[src:anja-karliczek/anja-karliczek] From 2017, she also served as deputy of Michael Grosse-Brömer in his role as First Secretary of the parliamentary group.
[src:anja-karliczek/anja-karliczek] In this capacity, she was a member of the parliament’s Council of Elders, which – among other duties – determines daily legislative agenda items and assigns committee chairpersons based on party representation.
[src:anja-karliczek/anja-karliczek] In addition to her committee assignments, Karliczek is a member of the German-Slovenian Parliamentary Friendship Group.
[src:anja-karliczek/anja-karliczek] Within the CDU/CSU, she is a member of MIT, its pro-business wing.
[src:anja-karliczek/anja-karliczek] She also belongs to the Münsterland Circle (*Münsterlandrunde*) which brings together all parliamentarians from the eponymous region in Westphalia; it also includes Sybille Benning and Jens Spahn, among others.
[src:anja-karliczek/anja-karliczek] Since the 2021 elections, Karliczek has been serving on the Committee on Tourism and the Committee on the Environment, Nature Conservation, Nuclear Safety, and Consumer Protection.
[src:anja-karliczek/anja-karliczek] From 2021 to 2025, she was also her parliamentary group’s spokesperson for tourism.
[src:anja-karliczek/anja-karliczek] In the negotiations to form a coalition government of the CDU and Green Party under Minister-President of North Rhine-Westphalia Hendrik Wüst following the 2022 state elections, Karliczek led her party’s delegation in the working group on research, innovation and digitization.
[src:anja-karliczek/anja-karliczek] Since 2025, Karliczek has been serving as chairwoman of the German Parliament's Committee on Tourism.
[src:anja-karliczek/anja-karliczek] In her capacity as minister, Karliczek was a member of the Joint Science Conference (GWK), a body which deals with all questions of research funding, science and research policy strategies and the science system that jointly affect Germany’s federal government and its 16 federal states.
[src:anja-karliczek/anja-karliczek] During Karliczek’s term, the German government introduced annual incentives worth 1.25 billion euros in 2019 aimed at supporting corporate research and development and boosting investments in cutting-edge technologies.
[src:anja-karliczek/anja-karliczek] In 2021, she publicly opposed proposals from the European Commission to restrict the right of scientists based in non-EU countries to collaborate in EU-funded projects on sensitive parts of the bloc’s €90 billion Horizon Europe scientific co-operation programme.
[src:anja-karliczek/anja-karliczek] As a representative of the German government, Karliczek was part of the delegation accompanying President Emmanuel Macron of France on his state visit to China in November 2019.
[src:anja-karliczek/anja-karliczek] In June 2017, Karliczek voted against Germany’s introduction of same-sex marriage.
[src:anja-karliczek/anja-karliczek] In 2018, she faced criticism after she questioned Germany's decision to recognize marriage equality in a television interview.
[src:anja-karliczek/anja-karliczek] In November 2018, Karliczek successfully suggested to ease the terms of the 5G build-out plan for network providers, declaring "we don't need 5G internet next to every milk churn".
[src:anja-karliczek/anja-karliczek] This was supposed to allow a slower proliferation of fast mobile internet in large parts of Germany in exchange for a larger amount to be gained by the federal government from the auction of frequency bands to operators.
[src:anja-karliczek/anja-karliczek] She married Eurowings pilot Lothar Karliczek in 1995; they have three children.
